cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.MM, cs.IR. 

The paper focuses on unsupervised domain adaptation for image classification, which is a common problem in computer vision. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a method that involves training a network to obtain domain-invariant embeddings with two critical characteristics, intra-class compactness, and inter-class separability, which falls under the scope of cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper uses pseudo-labels for target images, which is a common technique in semi-supervised learning, and thus, cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also a likely sub-category. The paper also evaluates its proposed method on two datasets, which falls under the scope of cs.MM (Multimedia). Finally, the paper involves aligning the distributions in the embedding space, which is a common technique in information retrieval, and thus, cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is also a possible sub-category.
